### Biography

#### Early Life

Michael Faraday entered the world on September 21, 1791, in [Newington Butts](/Newington_Butts), [Surrey](/Surrey)—now part of the [London Borough of Southwark](/London_Borough_of_Southwark). His family was not affluent. His father, James, a member of the [Glasite](/Glasite) sect, had moved his family from [Outhgill](/Outhgill) in [Westmorland](/Westmorland), where he'd been a blacksmith's apprentice. Michael was the third of four children, arriving in the autumn of the following year. His formal schooling was rudimentary; he was, by necessity, self-taught.

At fourteen, he was apprenticed to [George Riebau](/George_Riebau), a bookbinder and bookseller in Blandford Street. The seven years of his apprenticeship were spent reading voraciously, particularly [Isaac Watts](/Isaac_Watts)'s *The Improvement of the Mind*, whose principles he diligently applied. He engaged in discussions at the City Philosophical Society, where scientific topics were debated, and his fascination with science, especially electricity, took root. [Jane Marcet](/Jane_Marcet)'s *Conversations on Chemistry* proved a particular inspiration.

#### Adult Life

By 1812, his apprenticeship concluded, Faraday attended lectures by the renowned [Humphry Davy](/Humphry_Davy) at the [Royal Institution](/Royal_Institution) and the [Royal Society](/Royal_Society), alongside those of [John Tatum](/John_Tatum_(scientist)). A fortuitous gift of lecture tickets from [William Dance](/William_Dance) provided him access. Faraday meticulously documented these lectures, compiling a 300-page book which he sent to Davy. Davy’s response was swift and encouraging. In 1813, after Davy suffered an eye injury from [nitrogen trichloride](/Nitrogen_trichloride), he hired Faraday as his assistant. This position arose from a vacancy: one of the Royal Institution's assistants, John Payne, was dismissed, and Davy, tasked with finding a replacement, appointed Faraday as Chemical Assistant on March 1, 1813. Early on, Davy entrusted Faraday with preparing samples of nitrogen trichloride, and both were injured in an explosion of the volatile substance.

Faraday married Sarah Barnard (1800–1879) on June 12, 1821. Their families were connected through the [Sandemanian](/Sandemanian) church, where he later confessed his faith. They had no children. Faraday's deep Christian faith, specifically his Sandemanian denomination—an offshoot of the [Church of Scotland](/Church_of_Scotland)—permeated his life. He served as a [deacon](/Deacon) and twice as an [elder]((Christianity)) within his congregation, which relocated from Paul's Alley in the [Barbican](/Barbican_Estate) to [Barnsbury](/Barnsbury) Grove in [Islington](/London_Borough_of_Islington) in 1862, where he continued his elder duties for two years before resigning. Biographers note that "a strong sense of the unity of God and nature pervaded Faraday's life and work."

#### Later Life

In 1832, the [University of Oxford](/University_of_Oxford) bestowed upon Faraday an honorary [Doctor of Civil Law](/Doctor_of_Civil_Law) degree. He was offered a [knighthood](/Orders,_decorations,_and_medals_of_the_United_Kingdom) for his scientific contributions but declined, citing religious convictions against worldly accolades. He preferred to remain "plain Mr Faraday." He was elected a [Fellow](/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society) of the [Royal Society](/Royal_Society) in 1824 and twice refused its presidency. In 1833, he became the inaugural [Fullerian Professor of Chemistry](/Fullerian_Professor_of_Chemistry) at the [Royal Institution](/Royal_Institution), a position he held for life.

Faraday was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the [American Academy of Arts and Sciences](/American_Academy_of_Arts_and_Sciences) in 1832. He joined the [Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences](/Royal_Swedish_Academy_of_Sciences) as a foreign member in 1838 and was elected to the [American Philosophical Society](/American_Philosophical_Society) in 1840. The [French Academy of Sciences](/French_Academy_of_Sciences) elected him as one of its eight foreign members in 1844. In 1849, he became an associate member of the Royal Institute of the Netherlands, which later transformed into the [Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences](/Royal_Netherlands_Academy_of_Arts_and_Sciences), where he was subsequently made a foreign member.

Faraday House in [Hampton Court](/Hampton_Court), where he resided from 1858 to 1867.

He experienced a [nervous breakdown](/Nervous_breakdown) in 1839 but eventually resumed his electromagnetic research. In 1848, at the behest of [Prince Albert](/Albert,_Prince_Consort), Faraday was granted a [grace and favour](/Grace_and_favour) residence at Hampton Court, free of charge. This house, known as Faraday House, became his home in 1858.

Faraday's grave at [Highgate Cemetery](/Highgate_Cemetery), London.

Despite his service to the British government, Faraday refused to assist in the development of chemical weapons for the Crimean War (1853–1856), citing ethical qualms. He also declined to have his lectures published, believing that live demonstrations were essential for true understanding. "I have always loved science more than money," he wrote, "and because my occupation is almost entirely personal I cannot afford to get rich." A sentiment that seems quaintly out of place in today's world.

Faraday died at his Hampton Court residence on August 25, 1867, at the age of 75. He had previously refused burial in [Westminster Abbey](/Westminster_Abbey), but a memorial plaque now rests near [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton)'s tomb. Faraday was interred in the non-[Anglican](/Anglicanism) section of [Highgate Cemetery](/Highgate_Cemetery).

